</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>And so it goes for the other complex block types.</p>

<h3>Pattern Matching Is Stream Parsing</h3>

<p>In functional programming, your code is basically</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='elixir'><span class='line'><span class="n">input</span> <span class="err">→</span> <span class="n">some_function</span> <span class="err">→</span> <span class="n">output</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>You then use composition to break <code>some_function</code> into successively
lower levels of abstraction until you are dealing with primitive
values and built-in functions, at which point the decomposition can
stop.</p>

<figure class='code'><figcaption><span></span></figcaption><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='elixir'><span class='line'><span class="n">input</span> <span class="err">→</span> <span class="n">some_function</span> <span class="err">→</span> <span class="n">output</span>
</span><span class='line'>         <span class="n">__</span><span class="o">/</span>     <span class="p">\</span><span class="n">__</span>
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="o">/</span>           <span class="p">\</span>
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="err">→</span> <span class="n">fn1</span> <span class="err">→</span> <span class="n">fn2</span> <span class="err">→</span>
</span><span class='line'>     <span class="n">___</span> <span class="o">/</span>   <span class="p">\</span><span class="n">__</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="o">/</span>           <span class="p">\</span>
</span><span class='line'>    <span class="err">→</span> <span class="n">fn3</span> <span class="err">→</span> <span class="n">fn4</span> <span class="err">→</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure>


<p>If you look at it this way your program is basically a pipeline. A stream
of data enters it, gets analyzed, broken apart, piped
through a sequence of functions, mapped into something different, and
reassembled into the output.</p>

<p>That&rsquo;s where pattern matching comes it, destructuring the stream
of data and selecting what functions to apply.</p>

<p>And that&rsquo;s the cool part. If you think of your code this way, then
you&rsquo;re actually using pattern matching to parse the stream of data as
it passes through. If you can express your input as some kind of
grammar, then your program is something that transforms data that
matches that grammar.</p>

<p>This isn&rsquo;t just some kind of fancy abstraction, because knowing the
grammar you are working with can greatly simplify your code. For
example, if you know that your business rules are <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Context-free_grammar">context
free</a>, then you
also know that the code that parses and processes the corresponding
data can operate in isolation—it is automatically decoupled.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;d written code this way in Elixir, but hadn&rsquo;t really thought
about it in terms of parsing until now. Now I&rsquo;m starting to see more
and more of what I do in terms of grammars and production rules.</p>

<h3>An Aside—Listening to the Angel on your Shoulder (or the Dog on Your Rug)</h3>

<p>This writing of a Markdown parser is a
<a href="http://codekata.com">CodeKata</a> that I do periodically. Writing the
Elixir version, I confidently set off down the same road I took with
the Javascript version.</p>

<p>Now Elixir isn&rsquo;t as natural at string processing as Javascript. As a
result, the road started to get a little twisty. I found myself doing
nonfunctional things. I found myself writing longish functions. I
found myself worrying about the efficiency of various operations.</p>

<p>And I kept at it. I wasn&rsquo;t going to give in. It didn&rsquo;t feel right, but
I WAS NOT GOING TO BE BEATEN.</p>

<p><span class='caption-wrapper right'><img class='caption' src='http://pragdave.me/img/Rubber_duck_assisting_with_debugging.jpg' width='' height='' title='By+Tom+Morris+%28Own+work%29%3Cbr%2F%3E%5BCC-BY-SA-3.0+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fcreativecommons.org%2Flicenses%2Fby-sa%2F3.0%3E+or+%3Cbr%2F%3EGFDL+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.gnu.org%2Fcopyleft%2Ffdl.html%3E%2C+via+Wikimedia+Commons'><span class='caption-text'>By Tom Morris (Own work)<br/>[CC-BY-SA-3.0 <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0">http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0</a> or <br/>GFDL <a href="http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/fdl.html">http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/fdl.html</a>, via Wikimedia Commons</span></span></p>

<p>In the old days, I&rsquo;d describe my programming problems to a
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rubber_duck_debugging">rubber duck</a>. Nowadays
I&rsquo;ve graduated to Moose, a twelve-year-old black lab whose ability to look
disgusted at the ways of people is unsurpassed. When I grumbled
about the problems I was having to Moose, he simply raised an eyebrow,
turned over, and went back to sleep. Which, of course, is shorthand
for “if the code is telling you that it&rsquo;s hard to do it this way, stop
doing it this way.”</p>

<p>So I threw away perhaps a day&rsquo;s work and reimplemented it using
pattern matching and streams in an hour or two.</p>

<p>It just feels a lot better.</p>

<p>And that&rsquo;s one of the reasons to get into the habit of practicing code
kata. The fact that it took a day to recognize I was heading into a
swamp is very sad, but the kata let me make that mistake in a
noncritical environment.</p>

<p>I was doing the Markdown kata for the n<sup>th</sup> time. This
time I learned not to fall into the rut of doing it the same way each
time, and I came away promising myself I&rsquo;d listen to that feeling of
disquiet sooner in future.</p>
